ociopolitical ones; and underscore the category of form as a means for generating environmental-and therefore political-knowledge. Moving from the elegy and the industrial novel to the utopian romance, the scientific treatise, and beyond, Ecological Form demonstrates how nineteenth-century thinkers conceptualized the circuits of extraction and violence linking Britain to its global network. Yet the book's most pressing argument is that this past thought can be a resource for reimagining the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 4aEnvironment. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAllewaert, Monique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanerjee, Sukanya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrener, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHensley, Nathan K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHensley, Nathan K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKreisel, Deanna K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Elizabeth Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOak Taylor, Jesse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinkus, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShewry, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a